│ THOUGHT: The miscompilation comes from InstCombine transforming `select nnan c, (x * x), x` into `fmul nnan ninf nsz x, select nnan c, x, 1.0`. With the `ninf` flag, producing an        │
│ infinity is forbidden and results in poison. In the original IR, when `c` is false and `x = -inf`, the select yields `x` directly, avoiding the `fmul` and thus not producing poison.     │
│ After the transform, the `fmul` is always executed and produces `-inf`, which is poison under `ninf`. Therefore, the transform is unsound when `ninf` is present (and potentially in      │
│ other cases where moving the operation changes poison propagation). The fix is to update InstCombine to avoid sinking/hoisting `fmul` into/around a `select` when the `fmul` has `ninf`   │
│ (or any flag that would make executing it unconditionally introduce poison). I'll search for the pattern in InstCombine and add a guard to prevent this transform when `FMF.hasNoInfs()`  │
│ (and similarly consider guarding on other flags like `nnan` if needed).                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                           │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ grep -Rn --line-number --binary-files=without-match -E 'select .*fmul|fmul .*select|nsz|ninf|nnan' /llvm-autofix/llvm-project/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine && nl -ba                   │
│ /llvm-autofix/llvm-project/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp | sed -n '1,220p' && sed -n '220,500p'                                                                   │
